{{Japanese related|content| * [[Japanese/Grammar/Adjectives]]}} {{Japanese related|lesson| * [[Japanese/Lessons/I-adjectives]]}}
There are two types of adjectives in modern Japanese: な- and い-adjectives. Both are descriptive and modify nouns. They describe nouns and form predicates differently.
The な-adjectives (形容動詞, けいようどうし) conjugate with nouns by appending "〜な" before the following noun.
== Watch and Listen == Listen to the teacher read the following phrases, or click {{audio|Ja-Na-adjectives watch and listen.ogg|here}} to listen on your computer. {| class="wikitable" style="font-size:2em" |- style="font-size:.5em" ! Adjective || Noun || Adjective and noun |- |{{furi|元気|げんき}}だ。 |{{furi|人|ひと}}だ。 |{{furi|元気|げんき}}な{{furi|人|ひと}}だ。 |- |{{furi|奇麗|きれい}}だ。 |{{furi|女|おんな}}だ。 |{{furi|奇麗|きれい}}な{{furi|女|おんな}}だ。 |- |ハンサムだ。 |{{furi|男|おとこ}}だ。 |ハンサムな{{furi|男|おとこ}}だ。 |- |{{furi|優秀|ゆうしゅう}}だ。 |{{furi|学生|がくせい}}だ。 |{{furi|優秀|ゆうしゅう}}な{{furi|学生|がくせい}}だ。 |- |{{furi|有名|ゆうめい}}だ。 |{{furi|歌手|かしゅ}}だ。 |{{furi|有名|ゆうめい}}な{{furi|歌手|かしゅ}}だ。 |- |{{furi|大切|たいせつ}}だ。 |{{furi|授業|じゅぎょう}}だ。 |{{furi|大切|たいせつ}}な{{furi|授業|じゅぎょう}}だ。 |- |{{furi|簡単|かんたん}}だ。 |{{furi|宿題|しゅくだい}}だ。 |{{furi|簡単|かんたん}}な{{furi|宿題|しゅくだい}}だ。 |}
== Vocabulary == {{Japanese vocabulary entry|begin}} <caption>Nouns</caption> {{Japanese vocabulary entry | english = person, people | japanese=人 | reading =ひと }} {{Japanese vocabulary entry | english = woman | japanese=女 | reading =おんな }} {{Japanese vocabulary entry | english = man | japanese=男 | reading =おとこ }} {{Japanese vocabulary entry | english =class (session, not group of people), lecture | japanese=授業 | reading =じゅぎょう }} {{Japanese vocabulary entry | english =homework | japanese=宿題 | reading =しゅくだい }} {{Japanese vocabulary entry|end}} {{Japanese vocabulary entry|begin}} <caption>な-adjectives</caption> {{Japanese vocabulary entry | english = beautiful; clean, tidy | japanese=奇麗 | reading =きれい }} {{Japanese vocabulary entry | english =handsome | japanese=ハンサム | reading =ハンサム }} {{Japanese vocabulary entry | english =excellent | japanese=優秀 | reading =ゆうしゅう }} {{Japanese vocabulary entry | english =famous | japanese=有名 | reading =ゆうめい }} {{Japanese vocabulary entry | english =important | japanese=大切 | reading =たいせつ }} {{Japanese vocabulary entry | english =simple, easy | japanese=簡単 | reading =かんたん }} {{Japanese vocabulary entry|end}}
== Grammar ==
=== な-Adjective Predicates ===
When used as predicates, な-adjectives behave just like nouns: {| class="wikitable" | rowspan=2 | <な-adjective> || です |- | だ |}
Examples: {| {{Japanese example}} | {{furi|奇麗|きれい}}です。 || (She) is pretty. (formal) |- | {{furi|有名|ゆうめい}}です。 || (It) is famous. (formal) |- | {{furi|簡単|かんたん}}です。 || (This) is simple. (formal) |- | {{furi|元気|げんき}}だ。 || (I'm) well. (informal) |- | ハンサムだ。 || (He) is handsome. (informal) |- | {{furi|優秀|ゆうしゅう}}だ。 || (They) are bright. (informal) |- | {{furi|大切|たいせつ}}だ。 || (That) is important. (informal) |}
{{Japanese related|lesson| * [[Japanese/Lessons/Personal pronouns]] }} Note that the pronouns are usually dropped when they can be inferred from context. The pronouns in the English version are examples only to make better formed English sentences. For example, "{{furi|元気|げんき}}だ" can mean any of: "I'm well," "He's well," "They're well," etc.
=== な-Adjectives noun modifiers === When preceding a modified noun, な-adjectives take a "な" before the noun: {| class="wikitable" | rowspan=2 | <な-adjective> な <noun> || です |- | だ |}
Examples: {| class="wikitable" ! English || Adjective || noun || sentence |- | a healthy person || {{furi|元気|げんき}} || {{furi|人|ひと}} | {{furi|元気|げんき}}な{{furi|人|ひと}}です。 |- | a famous doctor || {{furi|有名|ゆうめい}} || {{furi|医者|いしゃ}} | {{furi|有名|ゆうめい}}な{{furi|医者|いしゃ}}です。 |- | an important class || {{furi|大切|たいせつ}} || {{furi|授業|じゅぎょう}} | {{furi|大切|たいせつ}}な{{furi|授業|じゅぎょう}}です。 |}
== Practice ==
Try writing and speaking out the following sentences in Japanese: {{col-begin|bgColor=#FFFFE0}} {{col-break}} '''Formal Japanese''' #I am well. #He is bright. #She is famous. #That is simple. #She is a pretty woman. #He is a healthy man. #This is an important class. #They are bright students. {{col-break}} '''Informal Japanese''' #He is famous. #She is well. #They are bright. #This is important. #He is a handsome man. #She is an important person. #This is a tidy classroom. #They are healthy students. {{col-end}}
Other ideas for practice include: * Write な-adjectives on pieces of paper along with nouns and keep these in separate stacks. Pick one of each and say the sentence. * Now write the English on the other side and repeat, this time translating as well. * Make pictures to represent the sentences and drill with those. * Write a short story or describe something that happened to you.
If you need help gathering adjectives, you can [http://smart.fm/goals/search?keyword=adjectives search for lists] on [http://smart.fm smart.fm]. To check your story, you can post it on [http://lang-8.com Lang-8].
